<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="470" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1323,1485]" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,1323,1346]" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the Chinese Village of Huangyong. The specific epithet is an adjective in the nominative singular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="470" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1323,1485]" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1392,1415]" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">Distribution.</emphasis>
So far known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[653,699,1392,1415]" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">type</typeStatus>
locality: 
<collectingCountry box="[800,868,1392,1415]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">China</collectingCountry>
: Zhejiang Province. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1427,1450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">Habitat.</emphasis>
Temporary stream in Bamboo forest, ca. 
<quantity box="[759,823,1427,1450]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="470" unit="m" value="0.5">0.5 m</quantity>
wide, slowly flowing, with gravels, sand and decaying leaves (
<figureCitation box="[232,298,1462,1485]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 2" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1234,1256]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,175,1213]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,161,1213]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 2. Microdytes huangyongensis sp. n. 1) Habitus and colour pattern of the holotype. 2) Habitat, photographed by D. Bian (China: Zhejiang, Lishui, Longquan)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/234569/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="470">
Fig. 
<number box="[282,298,1462,1485]" pageId="1" pageNumber="470" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
